From scratch logistic regression trained on NSL-KDD, plotting ROC and using Youden's J statistic to find an optimal threshold.
{list of achieved metrics once i'm done with regularisation}
As an intrusion detection system is the first line of defence for a network, the cost of a missed attack (false negative) is extremely high. Missed attacks could lead to severe data breaches, ransomeware deployment, network compromise etc.
The resources wasted on a false positive are minor compared to the damage a missed attack could cause.
Thus, in this model I optimised for recall (true positive rate) to be as high as possible. 
This was at the cost of having a high false positive rate. This is also harmful, as the security team will be overwhelmed by alerts and may pay less attention to valid warnings.
In conclusion, I deam the logistic regression model to not be effective as an IDS. Optimising for a high F2-score (weighing recall heavier than precision) was a monumental task.

This led me to investigate the effectiveness of a Decision Tree model.
